learning_outcomes.en:
Students will learn how design and semiotics consist of two processes: the linear, deliberate act that aims at a target and the non-linear, unexpected outcome that emerges. There is an overall emphasis in the course, as applied theory, to elaborate on the roles of subject, object, and environment as a grounding for co-development. 

List of outcomes
1.Understand deliberate acts versus intentionality during a design process;
2.Ability to use semiotic components as an apparatus towards real-world scenarios;
3.How to package a design deliverable using semiotic components to provide to a stakeholder;
4.Gain experience in solving practical assignments, project management and teamwork.

learning_outcomes.et:
-erialaste teadmiste seostamisvõime eluliste situatsioonide ja ülesannetega;
-oskus kasutada semiootika teooriaid ja meetodeid praktiliste probleemide tuvastamisel, hindamisel ja lahendamisel ning eesmärgipäraselt põimida teiste valdkondade vahenditega;
-kogemus erinevate uurimisviiside kasutamisel andmete kogumisel, analüüsimisel ning tulemuste mõtestamisel;
-praktilise ülesande lahendamise, projektijuhtimise ja meeskonnatöö kogemus.

description.et:
Course introduction;
Overview of coursework;
Introduce the projects the students can choose for a final project;
Discussion on how to navigate yourself in the course using deliberate acts and intentionality.

Exploring the role of the user
Communication and metacommunicative processes;
Distinguishing what is the rhematic versus dicent user;
How to frame the target users and key stakeholders for the final projects.

The environment as a designed system
Co-development process of user and environment; 
Physical and Digital environments as grounds for meaning-making;
Discuss the homework 1 assignment due before next class.

Modeling the Artifact and the desired outcome
How to anticipate user interactions of an artifact;
Distinction of technology and technics;
Discuss the beginning steps for the chosen final project.

Semiotic components as an apparatus
Learning what the four semiotic components consist of;
Explore how the components vary per different types of user interactions.

Distinction of Things and Objects
The relation of the mind and environment for the human lifeworld;
Synthesizing the semiotic components to things and objects;
Discuss the homework 3 assignment due before next class.

Exploring the world of affordances and tones
Distinguishing the objectivity of affordances and the subjectivity of tones;
Creative exercise in class to expand the horizon of perceived affordances;
Class discussion of potential tones related to course projects.

Degrees of Nature and Semiotic Ecology
Overview on the four degrees of nature;
Explaining the importance of paradoxical thinking for the nature of physical reality and hyperreality;
Identifying the characteristics of an immersed human lifeworld;
Discuss the homework 4 assignment due next class.

A recap of Designer-Artifact-User systems
Discussion about the theories taught leading up to this seminar;
Identifying and going beyond the barriers related to the final projects.

Constructing a design deliverable
Learning how to translate semiotic terminology into relevant information for key stakeholders;
How to effectively write about the deliberate acts and unexpected outcomes for the final project.
